page.title: 19TREES IN KEMPSTON
page.content: {URBAN KEMPSTON}The number and variety of species varies from street to street. The{newer estates}have been planned with open areas where trees have been planted.{Old deciduous trees have been built around and used as a feature. Where they have been planted along the street they have been well spaced out.{Vandalism}is a problem {AROUND KEMPSTON RURAL SCHOOL }All mature elm trees died of Dutch elm disease in the '70s.{Church Walk,}30 limes with ash & young elms.{Riverside over 20 willows & 60 alders.{Church- {yard}15 mature yews, 13 elders, 5 ash, 7 hollies & 1 horse chestnut.{The {Spinney}24 sycamores, 30 young elms,13 elders, 2 hollies, 5 ash & 1 large oak & beech.There are 2 great oaks in near by fields with a line of poplars near the{Bury.The Cemetery}has horse chest- nuts & a variety of coniferous trees.
